You’re right to pause here. Do not assume plain aerolitctl is using the code you just edited. It might be an older installed copy, or it might not exist yet.

For testing your current GitLab repo checkout, use this pattern from the repo root:

cd /path/to/aerolitctl/project
export PYTHONPATH="$PWD/src${PYTHONPATH:+:$PYTHONPATH}"
AEROLITCTL="python3 -m aerolitctl.cli"

Then use:

$AEROLITCTL version
$AEROLITCTL --help
$AEROLITCTL status

instead of:

aerolitctl version
aerolitctl --help
aerolitctl status

So the tests I gave you should mostly be the same, but replace every plain aerolitctl command with $AEROLITCTL.

Example:

python3 -m compileall src
$AEROLITCTL --help
$AEROLITCTL version
$AEROLITCTL configure --help
$AEROLITCTL configure init --help
$AEROLITCTL configure server --help
$AEROLITCTL status --help
$AEROLITCTL deploy --help
$AEROLITCTL deploy server --help

Then:

$AEROLITCTL path show
$AEROLITCTL bundle show
$AEROLITCTL bundle validate
$AEROLITCTL configure init --dry-run --non-interactive --verbose
$AEROLITCTL configure server --show

And this becomes:

$AEROLITCTL configure server --dry-run \
  --mode full \
  --interface ens160 \
  --server-ip 192.168.109.10 \
  --network 192.168.109.0/24 \
  --dhcp-start 192.168.109.100 \
  --dhcp-end 192.168.109.149 \
  --gateway none \
  --nfs-export-path /home/unix/bundle \
  --nfs-allow-clients 192.168.109.0/24 \
  --target-mount-path /home/unix/sysadmin

Then:

$AEROLITCTL status
$AEROLITCTL status --verbose
$AEROLITCTL deploy server --show
$AEROLITCTL deploy server --dry-run
$AEROLITCTL deploy server --dry-run --skip-interface
$AEROLITCTL deploy server --dry-run --skip-nfs
$AEROLITCTL deploy server --dry-run --skip-pxe
$AEROLITCTL deploy server --dry-run --skip-controller

When I said “installed command,” I meant this kind of thing:

command -v aerolitctl

If that returns a path, then aerolitctl exists somewhere on the system. But it may not be the code you just edited. To avoid confusion for now, use $AEROLITCTL for all testing.

After everything passes, then you can decide whether to install it in editable mode so plain aerolitctl points at your repo code, probably something like:

python3 -m pip install --user -e .

But for now, safest test setup is:

cd /path/to/aerolitctl/project
export PYTHONPATH="$PWD/src${PYTHONPATH:+:$PYTHONPATH}"
AEROLITCTL="python3 -m aerolitctl.cli"

Then run the same tests using $AEROLITCTL.